        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1072256" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6633653648498244909">I don&apos;t think you can read this book and continue to support the death penalty. Sister Helen Prejean&apos;s account of her personal experience is compelling, but when augmented with her cogent philosophical arguments, firm grasp of statistics and facts, and ability to calmly but firmly entertain and then quash every remotely plausible counterargument, the result will transform the way you think not only about this pressing political issue, but about punishment, humanity, and forgiveness. I think it s</span>
  <span id="freeText6633653648498244909" style="display:none">I don't think you can read this book and continue to support the death penalty. Sister Helen Prejean's account of her personal experience is compelling, but when augmented with her cogent philosophical arguments, firm grasp of statistics and facts, and ability to calmly but firmly entertain and then quash every remotely plausible counterargument, the result will transform the way you think not only about this pressing political issue, but about punishment, humanity, and forgiveness. I think it should be required reading.</span>
