<div id="review_3032933888" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3032933888" />
    <a title="Maeve M" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/101897791-maeve-m"><img alt="Maeve M" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3032933888?book_show_action=true">Nov 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maeve M" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maeve M" href="/user/show/101897791-maeve-m">Maeve M</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3032933888" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2708000664067443363">Dead Man Walking by Sister Helen Prejean, C.S.J is an interesting memoir about her time spent as the spiritual advisor to two death row inmates. It was published by Random House Publishing in 1993, in New York City. I recommend this book to anyone who is mature enough to handle this heavy topic. I would recommend that the reader is at least 14 or older. Helen Prejean is a Sister of St. Joseph from Baton Rouge, Louisiana. When she began her ministry against the death penalty, she lived in a housi</span>
  <span id="freeText2708000664067443363" style="display:none">Dead Man Walking by Sister Helen Prejean, C.S.J is an interesting memoir about her time spent as the spiritual advisor to two death row inmates. It was published by Random House Publishing in 1993, in New York City. I recommend this book to anyone who is mature enough to handle this heavy topic. I would recommend that the reader is at least 14 or older. Helen Prejean is a Sister of St. Joseph from Baton Rouge, Louisiana. When she began her ministry against the death penalty, she lived in a housing project in New Orleans. She was contacted by one of her friends, who worked with prisoners, and was asked to start writing to Elmo Patrick Sonnier. After corresponding with Sonnier a few times, she became his spiritual advisor and friend. He was eventually executed and that forever impacted her view on the death penalty. Some time after, she was asked again to advise another inmate, Robert Lee Willie. After her experience with him, she officially started many programs, including a program for parents of murdered children. I think this novel was fascinating and very eye opening. I never thought much into the death penalty debate but after hearing Sister Helen’s perspective, I now am interested in the debate and lean more against the death penalty now. I think one of the strengths of the book was seeing the perspective from the inmate, the family of the inmate, and the family of the victim. Even though, it was from a first person point of view, I was able to understand the perspective of every person in the memoir. I specifically found liked the part when she wrote Robert Willie’s last words. I thought they sent a very powerful message about the death penalty. Overall, I think the book was very well written and there were no weak sections. Though this book is very emotional, it is worth reading, especially if you’re interested in politics. This was an extremely eye opening book and I recommend reading it. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2708000664067443363" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


