<span id="freeTextContainer9069695852810560269">Sister Helen Prejean is truly prophetic in her witness from death row. She describes the unexpected path that led her to offer spiritual counseling to two inmates on death row and later to the families of their victims. She also makes a cogent argument about the immorality of the death penalty and our current justice system. I was finally inspired to read her book because she spoke over Zoom to the students at our high school. (I had already seen the excellent movie adaptation of this book a few</span>
  <span id="freeText9069695852810560269" style="display:none">Sister Helen Prejean is truly prophetic in her witness from death row. She describes the unexpected path that led her to offer spiritual counseling to two inmates on death row and later to the families of their victims. She also makes a cogent argument about the immorality of the death penalty and our current justice system. I was finally inspired to read her book because she spoke over Zoom to the students at our high school. (I had already seen the excellent movie adaptation of this book a few years ago.) One of my students asked her how young people like them can work for justice. She told them to start anywhere—as long as your heart is in it and you feel you’re doing what’s right.</span>
