<div id="review_4040790704" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4040790704" />
    <a title="Bernadette" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1538060-bernadette"><img alt="Bernadette" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1462317835p2/1538060.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4040790704?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bernadette" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bernadette" href="/user/show/1538060-bernadette">Bernadette</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4040790704" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9519624121607510314">Originally published in 1993, Dead Man Walking has been reissued and it rings more profoundly than ever. I won&apos;t attempt to review Sister Helen Prejean&apos;s amazing work. Her account of interacting with prisoners on Death Row, as well as their families and their victims&apos; families, along with her extensive research into criminal justice and soul searching moral arguments against the death penalty should be read firsthand and not interpreted. Highly recommend the book.</span>
  <span id="freeText9519624121607510314" style="display:none">Originally published in 1993, Dead Man Walking has been reissued and it rings more profoundly than ever. I won't attempt to review Sister Helen Prejean's amazing work. Her account of interacting with prisoners on Death Row, as well as their families and their victims' families, along with her extensive research into criminal justice and soul searching moral arguments against the death penalty should be read firsthand and not interpreted. Highly recommend the book.</span>
